We develop an algorithm for estimating the values of a vector <i>x</i> ε R<sup><i>n</i></sup> over a support <i>S</i> of size <i>k</i> from a randomized sparse binary linear sketch <i>Ax</i> of size <i>O(k)</i>. Given <i>Ax</i> and <i>S</i>, we can recover <i>x</i>' with ||<i>x</i>' -- <i>xS</i>||<sub>2</sub> ≤ ε || <i>x -- xS</i>||<sub>2</sub> with probability at least 1 − <i>k</i><sup>−Ω(1)</sup>. The recovery takes <i>O(k)</i> time.
 While interesting in its own right, this primitive also has a number of applications. For example, we can:
 1. Improve the linear <i>k</i>-sparse recovery of heavy hitters in Zipfian distributions with <i>O</i>(<i>k</i> log <i>n</i>) space from a 1 + ε approximation to a 1 + <i>o</i>(1) approximation, giving the first such approximation in <i>O</i>(<i>k</i> log <i>n</i>) space when <i>k</i> ≤ <i>O</i>(<i>n</i><sup>1-ε</sup>).
 2. Recover block-sparse vectors with <i>O</i>(<i>k</i>) space and a 1 +ε approximation. Previous algorithms required either ω(<i>k</i>) space or ω(1) approximation.